# pseudo-elements

A CSS pseudo-element is used to style specified parts of an element.

-> ::before pseudo element
This pseudo-element is used to insert some content before the content of an element.

for example:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
h1::before {
  content: url(smiley.gif);
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>This is a heading</h1>
<p>The ::before pseudo-element inserts content before the content of an element.</p>

<h1>This is a heading</h1>
<p><b>Note:</b> IE8 supports the content property only if a !DOCTYPE is specified.</p>

</body>
</html>


-> ::after pseudo element
This pseudo element is used to insert some content after the content of an element.

for example:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
h1::after {
  content: url(smiley.gif);
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>This is a heading</h1>
<p>The ::after pseudo-element inserts content after the content of an element.</p>

<h1>This is a heading</h1>
<p><b>Note:</b> IE8 supports the content property only if a !DOCTYPE is specified.</p>

</body>
</html>